# PostgreSQL / PL/pgSQL / Supabase Authoring

These rules come from real runtime bugs caught during P0 hardening. Each one
silently passed TypeScript/unit checks and only failed when the migration was
applied or the specific SQL branch executed. Treat every item as mandatory.

## Function bodies

- No explicit `SAVEPOINT` / `RELEASE SAVEPOINT` / `ROLLBACK TO SAVEPOINT` inside
  a function or `DO` block (SQLSTATE 42601). For per-item isolation use a nested
  `BEGIN ... EXCEPTION WHEN OTHERS THEN ... END` block, which Postgres maps to an
  implicit savepoint.
- `STABLE` / `IMMUTABLE` functions must NOT run `SET` in the body ("SET is not
  allowed in a non-volatile function"). Put `SET search_path = public, pg_temp`
  in the function header (between the `AS` and the body declaration), not inside
  `BEGIN`. Only `VOLATILE` functions may `SET` in the body.
- `format()` supports only `%s`, `%I`, `%L`, `%%`. C-style specifiers like
  `%.4f`, `%d`, `%f` raise "unrecognized format() type specifier" AT RUNTIME on
  the branch that builds the string. Use `round()` / `to_char()` + `||` instead.

## Supabase schema specifics

- `pgcrypto` lives in the `extensions` schema. Always schema-qualify:
  `extensions.digest(...)`, `extensions.gen_random_bytes(...)`. Do not assume
  these resolve from `public`.
- Inserting into `auth.users` fires `handle_new_user`, which auto-creates the
  `profiles` and `wallets` rows. Never manually `INSERT` those (pkey conflict);
  `UPDATE` the auto-created rows instead (e.g. to fund a test wallet).

## Migration discipline

- Retroactively editing an existing migration file is allowed only when BOTH are
  true: (1) git / Build Log evidence confirms the migration has not been applied
  remotely, and (2) the work report explicitly states why the retroactive edit
  was necessary. After a migration is remotely applied, every change must be made
  through a new migration file; never rewrite the applied migration.

## Function exposure & privileges (PostgREST)

- Every function in the `public` schema is exposed over PostgREST and EXECUTE is
  granted to `anon`/`authenticated` by default. A `SECURITY DEFINER` function
  with no internal auth check is therefore directly callable by any client.
  NEVER ship an internal helper or a generic balance mutator (e.g.
  `_credit_wallet_internal`, `rpc_credit_wallet`) that is reachable this way —
  `REVOKE ALL ON FUNCTION ... FROM PUBLIC, anon, authenticated` (revoke from the
  roles explicitly, not just PUBLIC). The definer `rpc_*` wrappers still call
  helpers internally because they run as the function owner.
- Client-facing `rpc_*` functions must guard on `auth.uid()` / `_is_admin()`
  inside the body; expose ONLY those.
- Views over RLS tables must be created with `security_invoker = true`, otherwise
  they bypass the underlying table's RLS (advisor: `security_definer_view`).
- Prefer the header `SET search_path = public, pg_temp` clause on EVERY
  `SECURITY DEFINER` function (not just `STABLE`/`IMMUTABLE`). A body `SET` runs
  after the `DECLARE` initializers, leaving them under the caller's search_path
  (advisor: `function_search_path_mutable`).
- After ANY DDL/migration, run the Supabase security advisor and resolve all
  `ERROR`s and any `anon/authenticated`-executable unguarded definer functions
  before considering the change done.

## Persistence vs. RAISE

- Side effects that MUST survive (circuit-breaker halts, audit/log rows, kill
  switches) must not be followed by `RAISE` in the same transaction — a `RAISE`
  rolls the whole transaction back and silently undoes them. Return a status
  object describing the outcome instead of raising.

## Conservation & balances (see also 30-money-ledger)

- Every balance-moving RPC must net `Σ(deltas) = 0` per currency across user
  wallets + system accounts. Decompose into quantized legs (user / fee /
  insurance / dust) so the sum is exactly zero; record bad debt as a metric, not
  as an unbalanced entry.
- Internal system accounts may go negative for liveness; user wallets must never
  go negative — enforce with DB `CHECK` constraints, not just app logic.

## RLS & table GRANT pairing (mandatory)

- Any migration that `DROP`/`CREATE`/`ALTER` RLS policies on a client-facing
  table MUST include the matching `GRANT`/`REVOKE` for `anon`, `authenticated`,
  and (when needed) `service_role` in the **same migration file**. RLS filters
  rows only after the role has base table access — policy-only changes without
  GRANT cause PostgREST `insufficient_privilege` or silent over-exposure.
- When adding or changing RLS on a table, update
  `supabase/tests/grants_rls_inventory_test.sql` with the new expected
  `has_table_privilege` snapshot for each affected role.
- Pair every RLS scope change with a `SET ROLE anon|authenticated` integration
  test (see `public_scope_hardening_test.sql`).

## RLS & auth in SQL tests

- The `postgres` superuser bypasses RLS. Do not `SET ROLE authenticated` in
  seed/test setup unless you specifically want RLS enforced.
- `SECURITY DEFINER` RPCs read `auth.uid()` from `request.jwt.claims`. Simulate a
  user with `set_config('request.jwt.claims', '{"sub":"<uuid>"}', true)`.
- For the service-role path (`auth.uid()` NULL) set claims to `'{}'` (valid
  JSON). Never use `''` — it is invalid `jsonb` and makes `auth.uid()` throw.

## Mandatory local apply gate

- A migration is not "done" until it has been applied to a local Supabase via
  `supabase db reset` (TS tests never catch apply-time SQL errors).
- Every money/settlement/liquidation/circuit-breaker RPC must be exercised by a
  SQL integration test that actually hits the changed branch, asserts the
  conservation invariant and hash-chain integrity, and `ROLLBACK`s (no residue).
  Keep these in `supabase/tests/` (`conservation_test.sql`, `hardening_test.sql`).
